I would classify the piece I chose from When Lightning Strikes by Noni Olabisi as both art and craft. It clearly reflects strong technical skill in composition, color, and detail (craft), but it also communicates a deeper message and emotional impact (art). What drew me to it was the bold imagery and storytelling—it 
immediately stood out and made me want to understand it. The piece evokes feelings of struggle, resistance, and empowerment, and I think the artist is trying to highlight social injustice and the fight for change. Personally, it makes me reflect on how history and inequality still affect people today. 
I don’t think Artificial Intelligence could fully produce something of equal meaning because it lacks lived experience and intent, even if it can mimic style. In terms of software, this connects to how I design and code: craft is writing efficient, functional code, while art is creating something elegant, 
intuitive, and meaningful to users. I believe software should be both an art and a craft—functional but also thoughtfully designed. When I code, I ask myself whether my solution is clean, readable, and scalable, and I do go back to refactor to improve it, not just make it work. Ultimately, well-crafted software, 
like this artwork, combines technical skill with intentional design and impact.
